  "output": "## Scope note\n\nThis directory (`apps/crawler`) is a pure Python crawler — no database queries and no React code live here, so two of the five requested categories don't map literally. I've translated them to the closest real equivalent in this codebase (redundant HTTP fetches instead of N+1 queries; no UI to re-render). Everything below is grounded in the actual files and, where I could, verified against real state data (state files already run 5KB–178KB, log files already have hundreds to thousands of lines with no rotation).\n\n## 1. Redundant fetches (\"N+1\" equivalent)\n\n**Moov spider fetches every page twice** — `providers.py:194-236`. `list_article_urls()` fetches each article page to discover outbound `/article/` links, then `crawl()` immediately calls `parse_article(url)` which fetches the *same URL again*. The code even comments on this (\"each page is fetched twice... acceptable for a small site\"), but it's a straightforward 2x reduction:\n\n```python\n# providers.py\nclass Moov(NewsSource):\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._page_cache: dict[str, object] = {}\n\n    def list_article_urls(self):\n        ...\n        while queue:\n            url = queue.popleft()\n            yield url\n            try:\n                page = Fetcher.get(url, headers={\"User-Agent\": USER_AGENT})\n                self._page_cache[url] = page  # reuse in parse_article\n            except Exception:\n                continue\n            for link in page.css(\"a[href*='/article/']\"):\n                enqueue(link.attrib.get(\"href\"))\n\n    def parse_article(self, url):\n        page = self._page_cache.pop(url, None) or self.fetch(url)\n        ...  # rest of shared logic needs refactoring into a helper that takes `page`\n```\nThis requires factoring `NewsSource.parse_article` to accept an already-fetched `page` (small refactor to `base.py`), but halves Moov's request volume.\n\n**No connection reuse across a run** — `base.py:163-166` and every `Fetcher.get(...)` / `urllib.request.urlopen(...)` call opens a fresh connection per article. A single provider run does tens to hundreds of sequential requests to the *same host*. If `scrapling`'s `Fetcher` doesn't already pool/keep-alive under the hood, wrapping calls in a shared `requests.Session()` (or checking if `Fetcher` exposes a session param) would cut TCP/TLS handshake overhead substantially, especially for sites without `needs_stealth`.\n\n## 2. React re-renders\n\nNot applicable — no React/frontend code in this directory.\n\n## 3. Caching opportunities\n\n**Sitemap re-walk has no cross-run memoization** — `base.py:62-88`. Sitemap *index* files (e.g., Midi's ~118 sub-sitemaps, `providers.py:18`) are re-fetched from the top on every run. The generator's early-stop (once `limit` new articles are found) mitigates cost only if new articles are near the top of the discovery order — worth confirming that assumption holds for all providers, since if it doesn't, every run refetches all sub-sitemaps just to filter by `seen_urls`.\n\n**`_discover_categories` (Tribune) re-fetches the homepage every run** — `providers.py:62-70` — to extract `rubrique` IDs via regex. Category IDs rarely change; caching the category list in state (with a TTL, e.g., re-derive weekly) would save one fetch + regex scan per run without losing correctness.\n\n## 4. Unbounded growth (\"memory leak\" equivalent)\n\nNothing leaks within a single process (each run is short-lived), but several structures grow **without bound across runs**, and that growth degrades future runs — the same practical symptom as a leak:\n\n- **State files never shrink or compact** — `_load_state`/`_save_state` (`base.py:139-150`). `malagasynews-mbs.json` is already 178KB of `seen_urls`. Nothing ever prunes old URLs, so both the JSON parse on load and the serialize-on-every-save (see #5) get slower every month, forever.\n- **Log files append forever, no rotation** — `_log` (`base.py:152-156`). Already 1,000+ lines for several providers with no cap or rotation. Add a simple size/line cap or switch to `logging.handlers.RotatingFileHandler`.\n\n## 5. Redundant computations\n\n**`get_all_text(strip=True)` called twice per paragraph** — `base.py:184-188`:\n```python\nbody = \"\\n\\n\".join(\n    p.get_all_text(strip=True)\n    for p in page.css(s.body)\n    if p.get_all_text(strip=True)   # <- computed again here\n)\n```\nThis re-runs text extraction/whitespace-stripping on every `<p>` twice. Fix:\n```python\nparagraphs = (p.get_all_text(strip=True) for p in page.css(s.body))\nbody = \"\\n\\n\".join(text for text in paragraphs if text)\n```\n\n**`sorted(seen)` on every single article save** — `base.py:304, 312` inside `crawl()`'s per-article loop. For a provider with N already-seen URLs, saving M new articles in a run costs `O(M · N log N)` just for sorting, plus a full JSON re-serialize + disk write of the entire growing list each time (atomic tmp-file + rename, `base.py:144-150`). With `malagasynews-mbs` at ~4,000+ seen URLs, that's ~4,000·log(4,000) comparisons *repeated once per saved article this run* — pure waste, since sorting is only for the file's diff-readability, not correctness (sets don't need order).\n\nFix — keep `seen` as a set through the loop, write it unsorted per-article (still crash-safe, still atomic), and sort only once when the run ends:\n```python\ndef crawl(self, limit=10, on_save=None):\n    ...\n    try:\n        for url in self.list_article_urls():\n            ...\n            seen.add(url)\n            state[\"seen_urls\"] = list(seen)   # no sort per-iteration\n            ...\n            self._save_state(state)\n            ...\n    finally:\n        state[\"seen_urls\"] = sorted(seen)     # sort once, for the final on-disk file\n        self._save_state(state)\n```\nThis keeps the deliberate per-article checkpoint (needed for crash-resumability, per the existing comments) but removes the O(N log N) tax from every single iteration — the biggest concrete win in this codebase, and it gets worse every month as `seen_urls` grows.\n\n**Regex recompilation** — `parse_french_date`/`parse_numeric_date` (`base.py:91-114`) call `re.search` with a literal pattern each invocation. Python's internal regex cache absorbs most of this, but precompiling at module scope (like `_rubrique_re` in `providers.py:56` already does) is free and slightly faster:\n```python\n_FRENCH_DATE_RE = re.compile(r\"(\\d{1,2})\\s+(\\w+)\\s+(\\d{4})\")\n_FRENCH_DATE_ALT_RE = re.compile(r\"(\\w+)\\s+(\\d{1,2}),?\\s+(\\d{4})\")\n_NUMERIC_DATE_RE = re.compile(r\"(\\d{1,2})/(\\d{1,2})/(\\d{4})\")\n```\nLow priority — this one's cosmetic, not a real bottleneck.\n\n## Priority order\n\n1. Remove `sorted(seen)` from the per-article hot path in `crawl()` — biggest, easiest, compounds over time.\n2. Fix double `get_all_text()` call in article body extraction.\n3. Cache Moov's already-fetched pages instead of double-fetching.\n4. Add log rotation before log files become unbounded.\n5. Cache Tribune's category discovery; investigate sitemap early-stop ordering assumption.\n",
